definition: "Lipoprotein-associated phospholipase A2 (Lp-PLA2) is an enzyme produced primarily by macrophages within atherosclerotic plaques. It circulates in the blood bound to LDL particles, where it hydrolyzes oxidized phospholipids — the lipid oxidation products that accumulate in arterial plaques and drive local inflammatory signaling. Lp-PLA2 activity generates lysophosphatidylcholine and oxidized free fatty acids, both of which are pro-inflammatory mediators that promote monocyte recruitment, foam cell formation, and plaque vulnerability. Unlike hsCRP — which reflects systemic inflammation from any source — Lp-PLA2 is produced specifically within atherosclerotic lesions, making it a more vascular-specific inflammation marker."
why_it_matters: "Lp-PLA2 provides information that hsCRP does not: it reflects the inflammatory activity occurring specifically within arterial plaques rather than the body's general inflammatory state. A person with chronic low-grade systemic inflammation from metabolic syndrome will have elevated hsCRP; a person with highly active, unstable atherosclerotic plaques may have elevated Lp-PLA2 with normal hsCRP. The distinction matters because vulnerable, inflamed plaques — not just large plaques — are what rupture and cause heart attacks and strokes. Multiple prospective studies have found that elevated Lp-PLA2 is an independent predictor of coronary events and ischemic stroke, with particularly strong associations with stroke risk. The PLAC test (measuring Lp-PLA2 activity) received FDA clearance for stroke risk assessment in patients with coronary artery disease."

